	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2988596433">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-11-07</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2988596433" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2988596433" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey <a data-dsq-mention="disqus_1j0devjrso:disqus" href="https://disq.us/url?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdisqus.com%2Fby%2Fdisqus_1j0deVJRso%2F%3AHXOGroTi8LB5fiJhF0sUaaW-qX8&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">Ruslan</a>!</p><p>Yep, you can definitely do this :). With our setup, we didn't make any easy way, but effectively, you simply need to decode the JWT in the same way that we decode it in the authenticator. Basically, you can repeat the things we do here: <a href="https://disq.us/url?url=https%3A%2F%2Fknpuniversity.com%2Fscreencast%2Fsymfony-rest4%2Fjwt-guard-authenticator%23getcredentials%3A1mLbQGqrVm4XbsE_TsbdMEPq90I&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">https://knpuniversity.com/scre...</a> - grab the token from the header, and then decode it. Of course, it would be even better to take this code and put it into a new service class. Then, you could call that from your authenticator or from your controller. And alternative method would be to update your authenticator to "put" the decoded JWT "somewhere" - e.g. set it on a service... or even put it into the request object <code>$request-&gt;attributes-&gt;set('jwt_data', $data)</code> (where $data is the decoded JWT that we have in getUser() of the authenticator).</p><p>Let me know if this helps! Cheers!</p>
